# Manual InfluxDB Data Ingestion Using curl

This document explains how to manually insert data into InfluxDB 2.x using `curl` and Line Protocol.

# Prerequisites

- InfluxDB 2.x server access
- Valid API Token
- Organization name
- Bucket name
- Linux server with `curl`

# Multi-Line curl Command


curl --request POST \
"https://influxdb.renewgrid.in/api/v2/write?org=Ramtaranga&bucket=Ramtaranga&precision=s" \
--header "Authorization: Token loXQMisGXy_jkkRjxyRci_R4LMgMH-dwIbpkrgtwSJzoicjgdwHCXT99AHlQoh4pFqHrQNoC-h-cHvGKQNK-Jw==" \
--header "Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8" \
--header "Accept: application/json" --data-binary "wattmon_std_mv,dlid=2CFE8B10D345,did=HTmeter01,f=kWh_Total_Import value=110764 1779128940" 

or

# Single-Line curl Command
curl --request POST "https://influxdb.renewgrid.in/api/v2/write?org=Ramtaranga&bucket=Ramtaranga&precision=s" --header "Authorization: Token loXQMisGXy_jkkRjxyRci_R4LMgMH-dwIbpkrgtwSJzoicjgdwHCXT99AHlQoh4pFqHrQNoC-h-cHvGKQNK-Jw==" --header "Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8" --header "Accept: application/json" --data-binary "wattmon_std_mv,dlid=2CFE8B10D345,did=HTmeter01,f=kWh_Total_Import value=110764 1779128940"


# Command Explanation

## API Endpoint

```text
/api/v2/write
```

Used to write data into InfluxDB.


# Query Parameters

| Parameter | Description |
|---|---|
| org | InfluxDB organization |
| bucket | Target bucket/database |
| precision=s | Timestamp precision in seconds |

# Authorization Header

```bash
--header "Authorization: Token YOUR_TOKEN"
```

Used for authentication.

# Line Protocol Format

```text
measurement,tags fields timestamp

Example:

```text
wattmon_std_mv,dlid=2CFE8B10D345,did=HTmeter01,f=kWh_Total_Import value=110764 1779128940


# Data Breakdown

| Part | Meaning |
|---|---|
| wattmon_std_mv | Measurement |
| dlid | Logger ID tag |
| did | Device ID tag |
| f | Field identifier tag |
| value | Actual metric value |
| timestamp | Unix timestamp |

---

# Current Timestamp Example

Use current Unix timestamp dynamically:

```bash
$(date +%s)
```

Example:

```bash
curl --request POST \
"https://influxdb.renewgrid.in/api/v2/write?org=Ramtaranga&bucket=Ramtaranga&precision=s" \
--header "Authorization: Token YOUR_TOKEN" \
--header "Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8" \
--data-binary "wattmon_std_mv,dlid=2CFE8B10D345,did=HTmeter01,f=kWh_Total_Import value=110764 $(date +%s)"
```

---

# Successful Response

If data ingestion is successful:

```text
HTTP/2 204
```

or no output.

---

# Common Errors

| Error | Cause |
|---|---|
| unauthorized access | Invalid token |
| bad request | Invalid line protocol |
| bucket not found | Wrong bucket name |
| connection refused | Server unreachable |

---

# Verify Using curl Response Headers

```bash
curl -i --request POST ...
```

---

# Security Note

Do not expose InfluxDB tokens publicly.

Recommended:
- Store token in environment variable
- Rotate tokens periodically

Example:

```bash
export INFLUX_TOKEN="YOUR_TOKEN"
```

Then:

```bash
--header "Authorization: Token $INFLUX_TOKEN"
```

---

# Recommended Optimized Line Protocol

Instead of:

```text
wattmon_std_mv,dlid=2CFE8B10D345,did=HTmeter01,f=kWh_Total_Import value=110764
```

Prefer:

```text
wattmon_std_mv,dlid=2CFE8B10D345,did=HTmeter01 kWh_Total_Import=110764i
```

This improves InfluxDB performance and reduces tag cardinality.
